Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/standing-order/orderVersionContainedBy
Object: Relates an order version to the revision set it is contained by.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/standing-order/OrderVersion
Object: A version of an order contained by a revision set.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/standing-order/revisionSetCoversBusinessExtent
Object: Relates a revision set to the business extent which that set covers.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/standing-order/revisionTo
Object: Relates a revision to the fragment version resulting from the revision.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/standing-order/versionOfOrder
Object: Relates an order version to the order it is a version of.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/standing-order/orderedBy
Object: Relates an order to the House by which it was ordered.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/standing-order/revisedOn
Object: Relates a revision set to the date on which one or more orders contained by the revision set were revised.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/standing-order/orderVersionOrdinality
Object: Relates an order version to its position in the list of order versions contained by a revision set.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/standing-order/BusinessExtent
Object: Sets out the extent of business covered by a standing order as public business or private business.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/standing-order/Order
Object: An order is an FRBR-style work level item, wrapping different manifestations - described as versions - over time. It represents a platonic entity and associated intent.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/standing-order/revisionFrom
Object: Relates a revision to the fragment version being revised.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/standing-order/containedBy
Object: Relates a fragment version to the order version it is contained by.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/standing-order/suspensionPeriodOfFragment
Object: Relates a suspension period to the fragment that is suspended for that period.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/standing-order/SuspensionPeriod
Object: A suspension period is the time during which one or more standing orders, or fragments of standing orders, are suspended. A suspension period has a start date and, where specified, an end date. These dates are set out in the utility model. Some suspensions do not specify an end date, for example: the suspension of House of Lords Standing Order 10(6) (Hereditary peers: by-elections) pending a further report from the Procedure and Privileges Committee. An order or fragment may be 'suspended, for a period' or 'dispensed with, for a purpose'. Orders and fragments may be dispensed with on a case by case basis: in the House of Commons this is usually indicated by the presence of 'notwithstanding' in the text of the motion. The suspension period class only covers suspensions and does not cover cases where standing orders are dispensed with. The procedure maps have steps which express the dispensing of standing orders.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/standing-order/fragmentVersionContainedBy
Object: Relates a fragment version to the revision set it is contained by.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/standing-order/Revision
Object: A revision is a change to the text of a standing order fragment.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/standing-order/text
Object: Relates a fragment version to the text content of that fragment version.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/standing-order/versionOfFragment
Object: Relates a fragment version to the fragment it is a version of.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/standing-order/orderCoversBusinessExtent
Object: Relates an order to the business extent it covers.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/standing-order/revisionSetOrdinality
Object: Relates a revision set to its position in the list of revision sets. Allows more than one revision set to occur on the same calendar day.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/standing-order/
Object: A model describing standing orders for both Houses of Parliament, establishing persistent identification of orders and fragments of orders.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/standing-order/fragmentVersionOrdinality
Object: Relates a fragment version to its position in the list of fragment versions contained by a revision set.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/standing-order/suspensionPeriodOfOrder
Object: Relates a suspension period to the order that is suspended for that period.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/standing-order/FragmentVersion
Object: A version of a fragment of a standing order, contained by a revision set.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/standing-order/Fragment
Object: A fragment is an FRBR-style work level item, wrapping different manifestations - described as fragment versions - over time. It represents a platonic entity and associated intent.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/standing-order/number
Object: Relates a fragment version to its number as it appears, within a revision set.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/standing-order/RevisionSet
Object: A set of orders as they exist at the time of revision of one or more orders.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/standing-order/isMajorRevision
Object: Relates a revision to boolean describing if the revision is major: a FALSE value indicates only a change of case to the text content, a TRUE value indicates a major revision involving a change of wording to the text content.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/standing-order/issuedBy
Object: Relates a revision set to the House it is issued by.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/standing-order/House
Object: A parliamentary House, for example: the House of Lords.
